  "text": "Viruses were historically categorized on the basis of two somewhat related sets of criteria: the ability to infect T cells (T-tropic) or macrophages (M-tropic) or usage of the coreceptor CCR5 (R5) or CXCR4 (X4) for binding and fusion with target cells. Defining true macrophage tropism has been historically difficult due to the high level of inter-and intradonor macrophage variation, in addition to the fact that viral tropism/coreceptor usage is not always mutually exclusive [CITATION_1] . Two recent studies used the recently developed Affinofile cell line [CITATION_2] to titrate levels of CD4 and CCR5 and quantitatively evaluate CD4 and CCR5 requirements of both classically defined and patient-derived T-tropic (isolated from blood or lymph node) and M-tropic (isolated from brain or CSF) Env proteins. They found that M-tropic Env proteins are not CD4 independent, but rather are capable of infecting cells with very low CD4 surface densities [8,9 && ]. Furthermore, the conformation of brain-derived, M-tropic Env proteins had increased CD4-binding site exposure and alterations in the physical interactions with CCR5 compared with lymph node-derived, T-tropic isolates [9 && ].",
